    "recap_headline": "University of Michigan Athletics",
    "recap_text": "\u00bb Michigan edged Nebraska, 2-1, to secure its first conference win of the season.\n\u00bb\nKurt Barr\nand\nMax Debiec\nteamed up for eight consecutive scoreless innings to close it out.\n\u00bb\nDrew Culbertson\nand\nEvan Haeger\neach drove in a run in the win.\n\u00bb\nGreg Pace Jr.\nadded a single, a walk and a stolen base in the contest.\nANN ARBOR, Mich.\n-- The University of Michigan baseball team opened its weekend series with a 2-1 win over Nebraska on Friday (March 20) at the Wilpon Complex, home of Ray Fisher Stadium.\nMichigan (11-9, 1-3 Big Ten) carried a one-run lead into the ninth inning with\nMax Debiec\non the mound. Nebraska (16-6, 3-1 Big Ten) led off the frame with a single, but Debiec induced a 6-4-3 double play to quickly erase the threat. The Cornhuskers followed with a hit-by-pitch and a single to put the tying run in scoring position, but a groundout to\nMatthew Ossenfort\nat first base ended the game, stranding two runners.\nNebraska struck first with a sacrifice fly in the opening inning, but\nKurt Barr\n(3-2) settled in from there, retiring the side. The right-hander delivered six consecutive scoreless innings to close his outing, finishing with 10 strikeouts over seven innings while allowing just six hits and no walks.\nThe Wolverines evened the score in the second inning. With two outs,\nGreg Pace Jr.\ndrew a walk, stole second, and came around to score on an RBI single from\nDrew Culbertson\n.\nU-M took the lead an inning later, as\nCarson Luna\nopened the third with a single. After a flyout and popout,\nElie Kligman\nmoved Luna to third base with a single.\nEvan Haeger\ntallied his 10th RBI of the season with a two-out single, scoring Luna.\nAfter the third inning, Michigan managed just two additional baserunners, both via walks. Nebraska threatened in the middle innings, leaving runners on in both the fourth and fifth, but Barr closed his outing with back-to-back 1-2-3 frames in the sixth and seventh.\nSix different Wolverines recorded hits, while\nColby Turner\nand Pace each reached base twice via walks. Barr threw 108 pitches in the start, and Debiec secured the save with two scoreless innings.\nMichigan will continue the series on Saturday (March 21) at 2 p.m. at Ray Fisher Stadium. The game will be streamed on B1G+.",
    "watch_url": "https://www.bigtenplus.com/en-int/livestream/nebraska-at-michigan/2081055"
